******
[1]
Date: Fri 11 Mar 2011
Source: 7 News [edited]
<http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/-/latest/8991136/department-investigates-possible-encephalitis-case/>


Victoria's Health Department is investigating whether Murray Valley
encephalitis (MVE) [virus infection] as a possible cause of the death
of a man from north west Victoria. The man died in a Melbourne
hospital this week and the Health Department says his case is still
being investigated.

MVE [virus infection] is an inflammation of the brain; [the virus] is
transmitted by mosquito bite. It can lead to convulsions, coma, and
even death.

There has not been a case of MVE in Victoria since 1974. However it
has been detected in sentinel chickens last month at Mildura,
Robinvale, Kerang, Barmah, and Tooleybuc [see ProMED-mail archive
number 20110223.0595]. The member of parliament for Mildura, Peter
Crisp, says it is a warning for people in areas where mosquito numbers
are high. "Not everybody who does show positive to the virus will have
symptoms, and of course not everybody who has the symptoms will have
them serious," he said. "However it is a cautionary warning for
everybody that we need to be careful. We know it's out there and it's
something we all have to be aware of."

And tests are expected to confirm this week whether or not the virus
caused the death of a horse at Cohuna, in the state's north west. Vet
Paul Clavin says if laboratory tests confirm his diagnosis, it will be
the 1st case of MVE he has treated in his 23 years of practice.

[byline: Jacinta Allan-Gange]

