******
[2]
Date: 11 Mar 2011
Source: ABC [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/rural/news/content/201103/s3161450.htm>


Mosquitoborne Murray Valley encephalitis [virus infection] has been
found in horses in South Australia's Riverland. It comes following
similar findings and the death of a horse, in north west Victoria.

Veterinarian Dr John Hammond says 3 horses in the Riverland have been
diagnosed, and Primary Industries and Resources SA is investigating
the matter. "We've had horses that seem to have classic Ross River
Virus symptoms, with swollen joints and a bit of a fever and very
stiff and sore," he said. "We've had some horses that have had
neurological symptoms. They've been weak and wobbly and have had some
trouble walking."

--
communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The previous report of suspected MVE virus infections in horses (see
ProMED-mail archive number 20110311.0784) has now been confirmed and
there is a current suspected human case under investigation. The most
recent human cases of Murray Valley encephalitis (MVE) in humans in
Australia have occurred in the Western state and Northern Territories
in 2009, far distant from Victoria state. The active sentinel chicken
surveillance effort for detection of MVE virus transmission has
provided an early warning alert in Victoria after a 37 year absence of
human cases.

Recent heavy rains and flooding in Victoria, especially along the
Murray River have doubtless created a significant increase in mosquito
breeding habitats. MVE virus is transmitted by the common banded
mosquito (_Culex annulirostris_), which bites after sundown in the 1st
2 hours of the night. It is found throughout Australia. Avoidance of
mosquito bites it the only practical measure for prevention of MVE
virus infection. There is no commercially available vaccine.

An image of the common banded mosquito, the vector of MVE virus can
be viewed at the CSIRO (Australian Commonwealth Scientific and
Industrial Research Organisation) website at
<http://www.ento.csiro.au/aicn/name_c/a_938.htm>.

As Mod.CP pointed out in ProMED-mail archive number 20100417.1251,
MVE virus is considered to be close to Alfuy virus (together forming
the Murray Valley encephalitis virus species). Both species are
members of the Japanese encephalitis virus group of flaviviruses.

An interactive map of Victoria state can be accessed at
<http://www.maplandia.com/australia/victoria/regions-la-trobe-mildura.html>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of Victoria state in
southeastern Australia can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00I2>. - Mod.TY]
